calcium salts in cartilage, often leading to joint pain and inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChondrocalcinosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommonly associated with calcium pyrophosphate crystals\u003C/strong\u003E, which can lead to a condition known as pseudogout. This condition is characterised by the deposition of these crystals in the cartilage, particularly in the knee joint, causing pain and inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETypically results from uric acid crystal deposition\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of gout, not chondrocalcinosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimarily affects the axial skeleton\u003C/strong\u003E - Chondrocalcinosis more commonly affects peripheral joints like the knee\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeads to increased risk of ligament tears\u003C/strong\u003E - While joint damage can occur, it is not specifically associated with ligament tears\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERarely causes joint inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - Chondrocalcinosis can cause significant joint inflammation, especially during acute attacks\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chondrocalcinosis is often associated with the deposition of calcium pyrophosphate crystals.","Chondrocalcinosis can lead to joint damage and is associated with conditions like pseudogout.","Chondrocalcinosis is characterised by calcification in cartilage, often seen in the knee joint."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Datta HK, Ng WF, Walker JA, Tuck SP, Varanasi SS. The cell biology of bone metabolism. J Clin Pathol. 2008 May;61(5):577-87. doi: 10.1136/jcp.2007.048868. PMID: 18441154","Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59771"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18332"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59771"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T04:09:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T04:09:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11050"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74280"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"sel